pwd
Whenever you feel lost in the filesystem, call the pwd command to know where you are:

Bash
pwd
It will print the current folder path.

Key Concepts to Know About pwd
What it stands for: Print Working Directory.

Absolute Path: It always outputs the full path starting straight from the root directory (/), showing you exactly where you sit in the system hierarchy (e.g., /home/username/projects).

Useful Flag (-P): If you are inside a directory that is actually a symbolic link (a shortcut), running pwd normally shows the shortcut path. If you want to see the physical, actual directory path underneath it, use:

Bash
pwd -P